  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why are birth rates lower in developed countries?",
  "response": "There are several factors contributing to lower birth rates in developed countries. Here are some key reasons:\n\n1. **Economic Factors**: In developed countries, raising children is often associated with high costs, including education, healthcare, housing, and childcare. Higher living expenses can make people hesitant to have larger families.\n\n2. **Education and Career Aspirations**: Higher levels of education, particularly among women, are linked to lower birth rates. With more educational and career opportunities available, individuals may choose to delay marriage and childbirth to focus on personal and professional development.\n\n3. **Access to Contraception**: Developed countries often have better access to a range of contraceptive methods, allowing people to plan families more effectively and delay childbirth until they feel financially and emotionally prepared.\n\n4. **Cultural Shifts**: Societal changes and evolving cultural norms about family structures and gender roles have also influenced birth rates. There is sometimes less emphasis on traditional family models and more acceptance of individual lifestyle choices, which may include having fewer children.\n\n5. **Urbanization**: Many developed countries are highly urbanized, and urban living often does not accommodate large families as readily as rural settings. Small living spaces, busy lifestyles, and a lack of family support networks in urban areas can discourage having more children.\n\n6. **Increased Participation of Women in the Workforce**: With more women participating in the workforce, balancing career and family life can be challenging. This often results in delayed childbirth and smaller family sizes.\n\n7. **Healthcare Advances**: Improved healthcare means decreased infant mortality rates, which can lead to families choosing to have fewer children, knowing that the likelihood of their survival is higher.\n\n8. **Delays in Marriage and Childbearing**: People in developed countries often marry later in life, which can lead to fewer childbearing years and therefore fewer children.\n\nThese factors interact in complex ways, and their relative importance can vary between different countries and cultures.",
